Investigating How Clothing style vary by Season

Brand Visibility by Style: What Your Outfit Says About You

Athleisure (Sportswear) takes the lead, boldly shouting its name in the guise of giant logos and easily recognizable brand symbols. Branding here isn’t merely observed—it’s the uniform. It is a reflection of a society where image and performance are equated.

Formal and Old Money styles reside at the midpoints, leaning towards subtle refinement. Their branding is less self-advertising—perhaps a well-tailored suit with a discreet insignia or a luxury handbag whose excellence lies beyond any brand name. In those situations, refinement lies in what is unspoken.

And then there’s Street wear, the subtle revolutionist. Paradoxically, it shows the lowest mean number of branded elements, reflecting the taste that stresses individuality at the expense of corporate branding. Individuality prefers to overcome the desire to expose brand allegiance here.

Overall, they remind us that fashion’s not just about what you’re wearing—it’s about a message. Whatever it is you’re getting dressed for, your engagement with brand speaks volumes about who you are. And in such fashions as Athleisure, that engagement takes center stage.

Layer Up or Strip Down: How Weather Shapes Our Outfits

The second plot demonstrates how weather affects our comfort with fashion, revealing how people feel wearing their preferred styles in Cold, Dry, Hot, and Humid weather.

The winner with the highest average comfort score (~2.35) is Hot weather. It is easy to understand why—light fabrics, breezy outfits, and relaxed Athleisure looks make it easier to stay cool and stylish.

In contrast, Cold and Humid reduces comfort levels by a slight amount (~2.2), maybe because it’s difficult to layer without ruining your look. Think about hot wear on a rainy day or bulky jackets that are not really fashion-forward.

Dry weather scores lowest on the comfort scale (2.0), which is surprising. Maybe people are simply less bothered about or attuned to this one when dressing, or it simply has fewer sensory or visual inputs that influence what they wear.

In general, the weather forecast might not dictate your sense of style—but it definitely makes you feel comfortable in it.

Accessorize with the Weather: What’s Hot and What’s Not

In this char, it is showcased how the weather influences our accessory fashion, and it’s a fascinating look at fashion’s practical side! Watches are the undisputed champions, especially in Dry weather, reaching a count of 4—clearly, people love a stylish watch when the air is dry and cool. Earrings and Other accessories tie for second place, with each reaching a peak of 3 in Cold, showing admiration for a little bit of sparkle or pizzaz when dressing up for cold weather. Scarves remain low-key, with a top of 1 in any weather—perhaps they’re reserving themselves for a good cold snap! Hot and Humid weather have more balanced accessory use, with figures around 1-2, as lighter dress promotes less showy adornments. It’s clear weather doesn’t simply control temperature—it controls style for our accessories, balancing form with flair as we move through the elements!

Trend Walk: How Footwear Styles Change Each Month

Looking at this graph, it’s pretty clear we’re seeing seasonal shoe trends in action! Sport shoes take a wild ride - super popular in March, then drop way down in April before climbing back up in May. Guess people’s workout routines change with the weather! Sneakers are the reliable friend here, staying steady at 3 units all three months - people love their everyday kicks no matter what. Jandals are slowly making their comeback as summer approaches, while heels just hang out at minimal levels throughout. Interestingly, boots and sandals don’t show up at all during these months - we’re catching that awkward in-between season when it’s not quite cold enough for boots but not warm enough for full sandal weather yet. It’s cool to see how our footwear naturally shifts from closed-toe to more open styles as the temperature climbs!

In conclusion

Along the route, I learned how weather determines accessories, how footwear varies by month, and how brands capture style personalities. Through some simple data transformations and plots, I gained more insight into fashion’s trends. While my results are specific to my observations and could contain some bias, this activity illustrates how data logging and visualization can reveal trends to make style decisions more informed.
